tockpiles^Freeport raised additional cash from investors during April 1922, giving each shareholder the right to subscribe to $8 of a bond issue for each share they held. The $4 million 7% 15-year bonds dated Apr 1, 1922 were issued on occasion of the signing of the Hoskins Mound contract with Texaco and the resumption of operations at Bryan Mound after a year of pause and were convertible to common stock at any time, 29 shares for each $500 of the bonds with the exchange ratio decreasing per quarter to a final 17 shares per $500 after May 1, 1923.[13] On Dec 31, 1924 729,844 of the 732,000 authorized shares were outstanding,[14] almost the entire bond issue was subscribed to and converted at the high ratio. Freeport had thus raised almost $4 million at a little over $17 per share.[15]^each preferred share convertible to 3+1\u20443 common shares on or before Feb 1, 1938 and 2.5 common shares thereafter and on or before Feb 1, 1945^36,822 includes the 732,000-729,844 that were previously unissued^In Feb 1933 25,000 shares of par $100 convertible[c] preferred stock were issued to finance the development of Grande Ecaille. The 729,844 no par shares with a book value of $10.0336 were exchanged for an equal amount of par $10 common shares (the difference added to surplus) and the authorized capital was increased by (1) 83,334 shares to provide headroom for the conversion of the preferred and (2) authority to issue 36,822 shares[d] for other purposes subject to Board approval, resulting in a new total of 850,000 authorized par $10 shares.[16][17] In 1933 54,747 common shares were issued as a result of conversion.[18] The company used cash to redeem on March 15, 1938 all 12,301 remaining 6% convertible preferred shares[19] (on Dec 31, 1938 there were 796,380 common shares outstanding[20]).^was organized in the spring of 1911, associated with the Houston & Brazos Valley RR, primary business was a steamship line between New York City and Freeport. Ships in service were:\nHon